{{Infobox organization |name=Jhpiego |logo= |type= |founded_date=1973<ref name="Jhpiego - Who We Are">[http://www.jhpiego.org/about/who.htm Jhpiego - Who We Are]</ref> |founder= |location=[[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]] |origins= |key_people=Leslie D. Mancuso, PhD, RN, FAAN, President and [[chief executive officer|CEO]] |area_served=Global |focus=[[Healthcare]], [[Malaria]], [[Maternal Health]] |method=Donations and Grants |revenue= |endowment= |num_employees= |owner= |Non-profit_slogan=innovating to save lives |former name=Johns Hopkins Program for International Education in Gynecology and Obstetrics |homepage={{URL|http://www.jhpiego.org/|www.jhpiego.org}} }}
'''Jhpiego''' is an "international non-profit health organization affiliated with [[Johns Hopkins University]]."<ref name="USAID/Afghanistan - Implementing Partner">[http://afghanistan.usaid.gov/en/Partner.70.aspx USAID/Afghanistan - Implementing Partner]</ref> The group was founded in 1973 and initially called the Johns Hopkins Program for International Education in Gynecology and Obstetrics, but is now referred to simply as Jhpiego (pronounced "ja-pie-go").
==Current program areas==
In its early years, Jhpiego was recognized as an expert in reproductive health and family planning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jhpiego.org/content/jhpiego-history |title=Jhpiego: A History |work=jhpiego.org |accessdate=28 May 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429062114/http://www.jhpiego.org/content/jhpiego-history |archivedate=29 April 2015 |df= }}</ref> As the organization has grown and become more field-based, its programming areas have grown and expanded. As of 2015, Jhpiego's primary program areas are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jhpiego.org/en/content/what-we-do|title=What We Do|work=jhpiego.org|accessdate=28 May 2015}}</ref> * Maternal, newborn, and child health * Family planning and reproductive health * HIV/AIDS prevention and care * Infection prevention and control * Malaria prevention and treatment * Cervical cancer prevention and treatment * Tuberculosis (TB) * Urban and community health * Education and training * Innovations
