[[File:Mabel Isabel Wilcox 1911.jpg|thumb|150px|Mabel Isabel Wilcox at Johns Hopkins School of Nursing c.1911]]
'''Mabel Isabel Wilcox''' (November 4, 1882 – December 28, 1978) was a pioneering nurse on the island of [[Kauai]]. She served with the Red Cross in Europe during World War I, and was decorated by Elisabeth of Bavaria, Queen of Belgium and by the Mayor of Le Havre. She was instrumental in instituting public nursing services on Kauai and in getting a hospital built on the island.
==Family background==
She was born November 4, 1882, in the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]], on the island of [[Kauai]], as one of six children of [[Samuel Whitney Wilcox]] (1847–1929) and [[Emma Washburn Lyman Wilcox]] (1849–1934). Mabel's mother was a seminary student in Chicago in 1871 when the [[Great Chicago Fire]] occurred.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Wilcox, Noted Kamaaina of Kauai, Passes |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19972196/mrs_wilcox_noted_kamaaina_of/|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=The Honolulu Advertiser|date=July 29, 1934|page=1}}{{free access}}</ref> Her father was a Kauai sugar planter, manager of a cattle ranch, and sheriff of Kauai for 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Samuel Wilcox, Hawaii Builder, Is Dead At 82|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19972257/samuel_wilcox_hawaii_builder_is_dead/|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|date=May 24, 1929|page=3}}{{free access}}</ref>
Maternal grandparents [[David Belden Lyman]] (1803–1884) and [[Sarah Joiner Lyman]] (1805–1885), and paternal grandparents [[Abner Wilcox]] (1808–1869) and [[Lucy Eliza Hart Wilcox]] (1814–1869), had been sent to Hawaii by the [[American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions]] in [[Massachusetts]].{{sfn|Hawaiian Mission Children's Society|1901|pp=40, 70}} She was the niece of businessmen [[George Norton Wilcox]] and [[Albert Spencer Wilcox]].
Her sisters and brothers were high-achieving individuals. Sister [[Lucy Etta Wilcox Sloggett]] (1877–1933) was a civic leader on Kauai, and also the [[World War I]] secretary of the Maui chapter of the American Red Cross.<ref>{{cite news|title=School Board Member for Kauai Passes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19971726/school_board_member_for_kauai_passes/|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=The Honolulu Advertiser|date=December 29, 1933|page=1}}{{free access}}; {{cite news|title=Mrs. H. D. Sloggett of Kauai Stroke Victim (cont. from Page 1)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19971865/mrs_h_d_sloggett_of_kauai_stroke/|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin at Newspapers.com|date=December 29, 1933|page=2, col. 4}}{{free access}}; {{cite web|title=Sloggetts|url=http://imagesofoldhawaii.com/sloggetts/|website=Images of Old Hawaiʻi|accessdate=May 10, 2018|language=en|date=31 May 2016}}</ref> Sister [[Elsie Hart Wilcox]] (1879–1954) served as a senator in the Hawaii territorial legislature.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Territorial Senator:Elsie Wilcox Rites Today; Was Kauai Civic Leader|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19985722/elsie_wilcox_rites_today/|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=The Honolulu Advertiser|date=July 1, 1954|page=1}} {{free access}}; {{cite news|title=Miss Wilcox (cont. from Page 1)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19985759/miss_wilcox_cont_from_page_1/|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=The Honolulu Advertiser at Newspapers.com|issue=July 1, 1954|page=8}}{{free access}}</ref> Her older brother [[Ralph Lyman Wilcox]] (1876–1913) was a plantation overseer on Kauai;<ref>{{cite news|title=Ralph Lyman Wilcox Drowns at Haena|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19972411/ralph_lyman_wilcox_drowns_at_haena/|accessdate=May 20, 2018|work=The Garden Island |date=July 15, 1913|page=1}}{{free access}}</ref> brother [[Charles Henry Wilcox]] (1880–1920) served in the [[Hawaii National Guard]], managed sugar plantations, and had been a representative in the territorial legislature;<ref>{{cite news|title=2 Killed In Auto Accident On Kauai|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20146285/2_killed_in_auto_accident_on_kauai/|accessdate=May 20, 2018|work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin at Newspapers.com|date=June 21, 1920|page=1}}{{free access}}</ref> brother [[Gaylord Parke Wilcox]] (1881–1970) was Chairman of the Board of Grove Farm, Ltd.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaylord Wilcox, 88, dies on Kauai|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19972469/gaylord_wilcox_88_dies_on_kauai/|accessdate=May 20, 2018|work=The Honolulu Advertiser|date=July 17, 1970|page=B4}}{{free access}}</ref>
==Education and early career== She received her early education at home from a private instructor, transferring later to [[Punahou School]] on Oahu, followed by three years at [[Oakland High School (Oakland, California)|Oakland High School]] in California, completing her basic education at the college preparatory [[Dana Hall School]] in Massachusetts.{{sfn|Peterson|1984}}
Her parents discouraged her from a career in nursing, but she persisted in pursuing her profession at [[Johns Hopkins School of Nursing]], receiving her RN degree in 1911. According to Johns Hopkins, she was the first Hawaii resident to graduate from the school.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scher|first1=Betty Borenstein|last2=McComas|first2=Pamela|title=Who was the first person from Hawaii to graduate from The Johns Hopkins University School of Nursing? – Johns Hopkins Nursing Magazine|url=http://magazine.nursing.jhu.edu/2012/07/who-was-the-first-person-from-hawaii-to-graduate-from-the-johns-hopkins-university-school-of-nursing/|website=Johns Hopkins Nursing Magazine|accessdate=March 2, 2018|date=July 27, 2012}}</ref> Upon graduation, she remained in New York for several years, affiliated with the Buffalo Red Cross War Relief organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Buffalo Red Cross War Relief Organization|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19986602/buffalo_red_cross_war_relief/|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=The Buffalo Enquirer|date=November 18, 1914|page=5, col. 4}}{{free access}}</ref>
In 1915, she returned home to Kauai as an employee of the Territorial Board of Health.<ref name=DiesAt96>{{cite news|last=TerBRUGGENCATE |first=Jan |title=Kauai's Mabel Wilcox, 96, Dies|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19986652/kauais_mabel_wilcox_96_dies/|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=The Honolulu Advertiser|date=December 28, 1978|page=3}}{{free access}}</ref> Instituting the island's first public nursing services, she was influential in raising funds and getting the territorial legislature to allocate land to build the [[Samuel Mahelona Memorial Hospital]] at [[Kapaa, Hawaii|Kapaa]].{{sfn|Peterson|1984}}
==World War I== With the outbreak of [[World War I]], Johns Hopkins pediatrician [[Edwards A. Park (doctor)|Edwards A. Park]], working with the American Red Cross Belgian Commission, headed the Children's Hospital in [[Le Havre]] as a facility for refugee Belgian children. He appointed Mabel as head nurse in supervision over 15 other nurses, among whom was [[Ethel Moseley Damon]] of Honolulu. They provided medical care and a safe haven for the children, often putting themselves in harm's way behind enemy lines to assist refugee women.{{sfn|Peterson|1984}} In recognition of their war-time services, Mabel and Ethel were decorated with the [[Queen Elisabeth Medal]] by the [[Elisabeth of Bavaria, Queen of Belgium|Queen Elisabeth of Belgium]] and the Bronze Medal of the City of Le Havre by the Mayor of Le Havre.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sinclair|first=Jane|title=Hawaii's heroic women in war hospitals:Nurses from Mid-Pacific go halfway around the world following the flag of the Red Cross|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19986772/hawaiis_heroic_women_in_war_hospitals/|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin{{Subscription required|via=Newspapers.com}}|date=October 5, 1918|page=59}}{{free access}}; {{cite news|title=Island Girls Are Awarded Decorations|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19975330/island_girls_are_awarded_decorations/|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|date=May 14, 1919|page=2, col. 5}}{{free access}}</ref>
==Postwar career ==
Returning home to Kauai, she became the trustee and treasurer of Samuel Mahelona Memorial Hospital, and a probation officer of the Kauai County Juvenile Court. In the ensuing decades, she served in administrative and advisory capacities of numerous boards and institutions. Mabel and her sisters renovated the Wai‘oli Mission House, which had been the boyhood home of their father. The house is now part of the [[Waioli Mission District]] on Kauai.<ref name=Death>{{cite news|title=Community losses: Mabel Isabel Wilcox|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19975208/community_losses_mabel_isabel_wilcox/|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=The Honolulu Advertiser|date=December 28, 1978|page=10}}{{free access}}</ref>
She died at home on December 28, 1978, and is buried on the island of Kauai.<ref name=Death/>
